			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Anderin sat beneath a great oak in the lesser faydarks. Soaking up the fresh air, he stretched out and relaxed. Lesser faydark, what used to be such a dangerous place was now crawling with all kinds of adventurers. As upsetting as this was to Anderin, he still warded off Equestrielle and brownies so the "children" could come in and play.
<br />

<br />
Anderin glanced up, a smell so foul and distinct caught his nose. He jumped up grabbing his bow and swords, mounting his faithful white stallion Skotto and rode off swiftly.
<br />

<br />
"Fire," he whispered to his horse. "Fires from kelethin! Run fasters old friend!"
<br />

<br />
They lept over brush, logs, fallen trees. They ducked low lying branches and dodged tree trunks. Anderin and his friend, his faithful mount rode harder than they ever did.
<br />

<br />
Upon reaching a clearing next to the beautiful Fier'dal city, Anderin froze in horror. The city was on fire, dark elves ravaging women and children, slaying men and boys. The guard put up the best fight they could, but the numbers were incredible.
<br />

<br />
"Skotto find my daughter," Anderin cried jumping off his horse. "Take her to safety whether she wants to or not! I trust you old friend, please save her life!"
<br />

<br />
Skotto nodded and galloped off. Anderin's eyes grew pale white, a faint green aura surrounded him growing brighter. He nocked and arrow and let it fly. It flew true into its target, piercing the heart of a dark elf commander. This drew attention to Anderin, something he truly wanted.
<br />

<br />
"This is my homeland, you've killed everyone willing to fight you," he started in the tier'dal language. "Except for me. I am standing here, ready to fight, ready to end your miserable exsistance! Any who dare defile nature and my people, must go through me first and foremost, didn't you get the note?"
<br />

<br />
The dark elves ran in to attack him, Anderin's joke wasn't amusing to them as much as it was to him. With deft skill, his bow replaced upon his back, and swords drawn, deflected each attack. On the ripostes, Anderin gutted one dropping him straight to the ground like a rock. An arm cut off, a head rolled. Obvious by now Anderin was not an elf to be taken lightly. More attention was brought to Anderin now, giving time to those still alive to escape.
<br />

<br />
"I'll see you all in hell," Anderin shouted charging into the ranks of the dark elf raiders. "This is for my home, my people, and for no good reason at all!"
<br />

<br />
Swift like a wolf, he darted behind trees, into enemies, back behind trees or brush. Each attack killed one or more, each attack he retreated. His hit and run tactics worked so well the dark elves began to worry whether or not they could kill one man. But a ranger is at home in the trees, no one dare fight a ranger in his element unless they have a death wish.
<br />

<br />
This went on for several hours, finally Anderin tired and losing blood quickly sank to one knee. In front of him was his horse, standing over the body of his daughter. She lay naked and bloodied, she too fell when the dark elves attacked. Anderin looked around, the trees and the cities burned to ash. All that remained was the forest not yet set on fire. The Koda'dal hadn't even come to help, soon the forest would be nothing but cinder and ash.
<br />

<br />
"Why my goddess," Anderin said gasping for air. "Why have you stopped protecting us from evil, I tried doing this alone, and for what?! You let my daughter die?!! The one thing that matters more to me than you!! And you let her die!?!"
<br />

<br />
Anderin's eyes welled up, tears streamed down his face like a raging waterfall. They stung his wounds and washed the dirt away. But Anderin had given up, tossing each sword to the side and removing his bow. Anderin sat with his daughter's body in his arms, wrapped in his cloak. He rocked back and forth slowly singing an ancient song of the elves.
<br />

<br />
After awhile the dark elves came and saw Anderin greiving. They laughed and pryed his arms off and tied him up. Anderin was now a prisoner of dark elves, yet he didn't even seem to notice. After an hour of walking, he said softly.....
<br />

<br />

<br />
"When a ranger loses faith..... all hope is lost...."<br />_________________<br />"...we walk the dark paths that few seldom trod. We spend our sleepless nights defending the forests so you may travel safely. Our blood is spilt so yours doesn't have to be. We are the candle between the darkness and the light.... you're welcome..."  -- the calling of a ranger</span><span class="gentblsmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
