			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">been awhile since the first post of this. Not sure why, just never got around to adding more. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
Anderin was half coherant as the tier'dal guards were leading off prisoners of war. Many who were not able to fight surrendered to the attacking army. Anderin hadn't really surrendered, he was grieving when they chained him up and lead him away. The fires of neriak were spreading, Felwithe was next on their list. The city was being hit with catapaults and the main defense was crumbling slowly. Anderin peered over his shoulder, in the distance his acute vision could see paladins of the high elves charging head strong into the ranks of the tier'dal. 
<br />

<br />
"Fools," he cursed outloud. "All of them, without the forest they have no home. They didn't even organize a counter attack to save my people!"
<br />

<br />
Straight ahead of Anderin was a loud commotion. Many guards were fighting off what seemed like an invisible attacker. Blood sprayed the ground as fresh corpses fell like rocks. A hand grabbed Anderin and whirled him around, in a daze Anderin didn't even recognize his subbordinates.
<br />

<br />
"Captain," a young woman said. "Captain! we must get you out of here! Do you understand me?"
<br />

<br />
Anderin looked at her blankly for a moment; her face triggered his mind to snap out of his depression. 
<br />

<br />
"Lithania," he whispered. "Go on, get out of here before they catch you. Get the others and escape while you can. All is lost... hope has been foresaken..."
<br />

<br />
Anderin trailed off into mumbles filled with pain. Lithania rolled her eyes and punched her captain with all her might. Anderin shook his head and looked around unsure of where he was or why he was chained up.
<br />

<br />
"Snap out of it," she shouted. "I've removed your bonds, take your weapons and lead a strike against the tier'dal! They caught us off guard, that is where we failed you. But let us make up for it by fighting at your side now! You are hope, you are our faith!"
<br />

<br />
"They killed her," Anderin choked out with a tear rolling down his face. "My light has been estinguished from this world and I did nothing!"
<br />

<br />
"Then do something now," she pleaded, half dragging him into thicker trees. "Do not let her death be in vain, she fought bravely as you taught her. Many of us died hoping we would not disappoint you!"
<br />

<br />
Anderin grabbed his swords and his bow, then looked around. The remaining rangers of the faydarks that answered to him had appeared. Unsure of his ability to lead he closed his eyes to prepare his mind.
<br />

<br />
"Swift and quick like a pack of wolves," he growled. "We will strike and vanish as you've all be trained to do. If you can not walk, then you will be left behind.... but I will come back for you. You will not be forgotten."
<br />

<br />
Anderin checked his quiver and his bow then raced off into the trees. Like a man possessed, he continued to gain speed as he ran. The rest of them could only push on to catch up, but their strength began to fade.
<br />

<br />
Anderin burst out of the underbrush like a demon from the underworld. He caught a whole squad of soldiers off guard as he struck with lethal and deadly power. When he finished of the last soldier he vanished into the environment. Unsure of what just hit them, the tier'dal began to spread out and search the forest. The more they spread out, the more of them were slain by Anderin and his band of forest warriors. 
<br />

<br />
As time passed, Felwithe's outter wall had been breeched. The Koda'dal had fought tirelessly to keep the tier'dal out, but it was no use. Their superiour number kept pushing them back. 
<br />

<br />
"... when a ranger loses faith... run and hide... and pray he or she does not find you!" Anderin cursed as he sprung from a tree and landed on an auxilary commander and a couple captains. 
<br />

<br />
Before they could react, daggers cut their throats like lighting striking a tree during a thunderstorm. Anderin jumped to his feet and left his daggers sticking out from the chest of a tier'dal soldier. By the time the rest could react to this crazed ranger, arrows flew in from surrounding trees. So accurate they did not even come close to hitting their captain. Fifty more soldiers perished before the catapaults were unmanned. Tier'dal soldiers fleeing were chased down and butchered like sheep. 
<br />

<br />
"What now," Lithania said breathlessly. "If we go into the city, we lose our advantage. But if we don't go in, the koda'dal will surely fall."
<br />

<br />
"Let them fall," Anderin said while putting a new string on his bow. "They deserve to die like traitors! They believe they're so high and mighty compared to the rest of us... even our people who have been faithful allies for all time! When the battle worn tier'dal soldiers come out of the cit we will strike them down as we have done to their comrades."
<br />

<br />
Everyone looked at each other in shock. Anderin had completely lost it? To refuse aide to their Koda'dal cousins when they had numbers to do so was blasphemy in the eyes of Tunare and the code of the rangers.
<br />

<br />
"Sir," Lithania said in a low voice. "If we do not act quickly, it will be on our heads not theirs!"
<br />

<br />
Anderin glared at her for a moment then raced toward the ruined city wall. Peering in cautiously the twang of his bow screamed through the broken tunnels as several soldiers dropped to the ground.
<br />

<br />
"For death and glory," he shouted. "And for those who have lost their lives this day. May the wrath of nature be revered in all the world when this is over!"
<br />

<br />
Anderin let loose several more arrows as he raced in to meet the invading soldiers. The rest of them followed his lead, letting fly as many arrows as they could on the run, then drawing their blades to engage face to face with an enemy filled with pure hatred.
<br />

<br />
As the last soldier died, Anderin looked around to find all but eight of his subbordinates had lived. The Koda'dal lost many in the fight, but the bitter taste of hatred moistened Anderin's mouth. 
<br />

<br />
"The rangers never turn their backs on their bretheren," Anderin stated simply; then walked away into the forest.<br />_________________<br />"...we walk the dark paths that few seldom trod. We spend our sleepless nights defending the forests so you may travel safely. Our blood is spilt so yours doesn't have to be. We are the candle between the darkness and the light.... you're welcome..."  -- the calling of a ranger</span><span class="gentblsmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
